04513nam a22005295i 9780226285740DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015011404  a97802262857407 a10.7208/97802262857402doi  a(DE-B1597)568038  a(OCoLC)1233041033  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aRA395.A3bM86 2015 4aRA395.A3bM86 2015 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a330.9732231 aMulligan, Casey B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSide Effects and Complications :bThe Economic Consequences of Health-Care Reform /cCasey B. Mulligan. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b26 color plates, 4 halftones, 47 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- t1 The Paradox of Affordability -- t2 Too Good to Be True: The Health Reform’s Hidden Taxes -- t3 Some Unpleasant Penalty Arithmetic -- t4 Some Unpleasant Subsidy Arithmetic -- t5 Exchange Subsidies and Their Implicit Income Taxes -- t6 Consequences for Employee Work Schedules -- t7 Adam Smith’s Equalizing Differences: More Hidden Taxes and More Health Coverage -- t8 The ACA’s Productivity Distortions -- t9 Other Significant Causes of Economic Change, 2007–2017 -- t10 Romneycare Times Eleven -- t11 Conclusions -- tNotation Directory -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Affordable Care Act will have a dangerous effect on the American economy. That may sound like a political stance, but it’s a conclusion directly borne out by economic forecasts. In Side Effects and Complications, preeminent labor economist Casey B. Mulligan brings to light the dire economic realities that have been lost in the ideological debate over the ACA, and he offers an eye-opening, accessible look at the price American citizens will pay because of it. Looking specifically at the labor market, Mulligan reveals how the costs of health care under the ACA actually create implicit taxes on individuals, and how increased costs to employers will be passed on to their employees. Mulligan shows how, as a result, millions of workers will find themselves in a situation in which full-time work, adjusted for the expense of health care, will actually pay less than part-time work or even not working at all. Analyzing the incentives—or lack thereof—for people to earn more by working more, Mulligan offers projections on how many hours people will work and how productively they will work, as well as how much they will spend in general. Using the powerful tools of economics, he then illustrates the detrimental consequences on overall employment in the near future. Drawing on extensive knowledge of the labor market and the economic theories at its foundation, Side Effects and Complications offers a crucial wake-up call about the risks the ACA poses for the economy. Plainly laying out the true costs of the ACA, Mulligan’s grounded and thorough predictions are something that workers and policy makers cannot afford to ignore.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHealth care reformxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aHealth care reform-Economic aspects-United States. 0aUnited States.-Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226285740423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226285740.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles